{"parse":{"title":"Cover your ass","pageid":19636679,"revid":856650345,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Cover your ass</b> (British: <b>arse</b>), abbreviated <b>CYA</b>, is activity done by an individual to protect himself or herself from possible subsequent criticism, legal penalties, or other repercussions, usually in a work-related or bureaucratic context. In one sense, it may be rightful steps to protect oneself properly while in a difficult situation, such as what steps to take to protect oneself after being fired.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> But, in a different sense, according to <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_New_York_Times\" title=\"The New York Times\">The New York Times</a></i><span class=\"nowrap\" style=\"padding-left:0.1em;\">&#39;</span> language expert <a href=\"/wiki/William_Safire\" title=\"William Safire\">William Safire</a>, it describes \"the bureaucratic technique of averting future accusations of policy error or wrongdoing by deflecting responsibility in advance\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-twsSafire_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-twsSafire-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> It often involves diffusing responsibility for one's actions as a form of insurance against possible future negative repercussions.<sup id=\"cite_ref-twsSafire_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-twsSafire-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> It can denote a type of institutional risk-averse mentality which works against accountability and responsibility, often characterized by excessive paperwork and documentation,<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> which can be harmful to the institution's overall effectiveness.<sup id=\"cite_ref-twsAtlantic_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-twsAtlantic-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> The activity, sometimes seen as instinctive,<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> is generally unnecessary towards accomplishing the goals of the organization, but helpful to protect a particular individual's career within it, and it can be seen as a type of institutional corruption working against individual initiative.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Usage\">Usage</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Cover_your_ass&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Usage\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The phrase <i>cover your ass</i> is generally viewed as a <a href=\"/wiki/Vulgarity\" title=\"Vulgarity\">vulgar</a> term, often replaced by the less-vulgar sounding initials <i>CYA</i><sup id=\"cite_ref-twsSafire_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-twsSafire-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Safire identified <i>CYA</i> as a <a href=\"/wiki/Synecdoche\" title=\"Synecdoche\">synecdoche</a>, in the same sense that the word \"ass\" had come to reference the whole person.<sup id=\"cite_ref-twsSafire_2-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-twsSafire-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The word \"ass\" in the phrase is often replaced with more polite versions or other <a href=\"/wiki/Euphemism\" title=\"Euphemism\">euphemisms</a>, such as \"cover your actions\", \"cover your rear end\", or \"cover your butt\", according to Safire.<sup id=\"cite_ref-twsSafire2_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-twsSafire2-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> The \"cover your butt\" variant has been used in various ways, such as by Minnesota health authorities urging citizens to undergo preventive <a href=\"/wiki/Colonoscopy\" title=\"Colonoscopy\">colorectal exams</a>, as a way to \"cover\" themselves medically from possible future cancer.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> In banking, officers tasked with making sure the bank follows proper regulatory procedures, called <a href=\"/wiki/Chief_compliance_officer\" title=\"Chief compliance officer\">compliance officers</a>, may realize that certain dubious transactions, such as <a href=\"/wiki/Money_laundering\" title=\"Money laundering\">money laundering</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Terrorist_financing\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Terrorist financing\">terrorist financing</a>, will occur regardless of any regulatory restrictions;<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> still, to protect themselves and their banks against possible future sanctions, they may engage in CYA activity such as issuing unnecessary memos, obfuscating documents or conducting transactions discreetly, as ways to absolve themselves from possible future liability. The term is widely used in <a href=\"/wiki/Journalism\" title=\"Journalism\">journalism</a>. Safire explained how the term is used in <a href=\"/wiki/Bureaucracy\" title=\"Bureaucracy\">bureaucracy</a>:<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<style data-mw-deduplicate=\"TemplateStyles:r856303468\">.mw-parser-output .templatequote{overflow:hidden;margin:1em 0;padding:0 40px}.mw-parser-output .templatequote .templatequotecite{line-height:1.5em;text-align:left;padding-left:1.6em;margin-top:0}</style><blockquote class=\"templatequote\"><p>A bureaucrat adept at <i>C.Y.A.</i> (a) likes to employ passive constructions (see <a href=\"/wiki/Mistakes_were_made\" title=\"Mistakes were made\">Mistakes were made</a>), (b) follows up a meeting or phone call with a self-serving <i>memcon</i> \u2014 \"memorandum of conversation\", (c) routes memos to and through as many other bureaucrats as possible, thereby spreading the risk of future criticism, and (d) \"papers the file\" with memoranda sometimes supporting and sometimes contradicting his or her position.\n</p></blockquote>\n<p>Because these practices are so routine, a genuine warning can be mistaken for CYA behavior, causing a <a href=\"/wiki/Type_I_and_type_II_errors#Type_II_error\" title=\"Type I and type II errors\">type II error</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/False_positives_and_false_negatives#False_negative_error\" title=\"False positives and false negatives\">false-negative error</a>, with disastrous results. For example, in the summer preceding the <a href=\"/wiki/September_11_attacks\" title=\"September 11 attacks\">attacks of 9/11</a>, U.S. president <a href=\"/wiki/George_W._Bush\" title=\"George W. Bush\">George W. Bush</a> was briefed on a now-famous August 6, 2001, memo titled <i><a href=\"/wiki/Bin_Ladin_Determined_To_Strike_in_US\" title=\"Bin Ladin Determined To Strike in US\">Bin Ladin Determined To Strike in US</a></i>. Bush's response to the briefer was reportedly: \"All right. You've covered your ass, now.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In another example, before the launch of the United States spaceship Challenger which ended tragically with the <a href=\"/wiki/Space_Shuttle_Challenger_disaster\" title=\"Space Shuttle Challenger disaster\">Space Shuttle Challenger disaster</a>, the final launch approval by rocket maker <a href=\"/wiki/Morton_Thiokol\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Morton Thiokol\">Morton Thiokol</a> contained the phrase \"information on this page was prepared to support an oral presentation and cannot be considered complete without the oral discussion\"; this notice was later described as a \"CYA notice\" by information design specialist <a href=\"/wiki/Edward_Tufte\" title=\"Edward Tufte\">Edward Tufte</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> In print, it can have the form of a <a href=\"/wiki/Disclaimer\" title=\"Disclaimer\">disclaimer</a>; for example, <i><a href=\"/wiki/Slate_(magazine)\" title=\"Slate (magazine)\">Slate</a></i> magazine suggested that the <a href=\"/wiki/Executive_Office_of_the_President_of_the_United_States\" title=\"Executive Office of the President of the United States\">White House</a> used the phrase \"It is important not to read too much into any one monthly report\" as a disclaimer on reports, and this was described as a CYA activity.<sup id=\"cite_ref-13\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> The term has been applied in the medical profession to describe doctors who prescribe unnecessary medical tests for patients, to protect themselves against possible future lawsuits.<sup id=\"cite_ref-14\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-14\">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> The term has been used to describe a cultural tendency which works against accountability and risk-taking, such as in a war effort when generals engage in much <i>cover your ass</i> activity which avoids taking real responsibility.<sup id=\"cite_ref-twsAtlantic_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-twsAtlantic-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Cover_your_ass&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Due_diligence\" title=\"Due diligence\">Due diligence</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Mistakes_were_made\" title=\"Mistakes were made\">Mistakes were made</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Plausible_deniability\" title=\"Plausible deniability\">Plausible deniability</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Principal%E2%80%93agent_problem\" title=\"Principal\u2013agent problem\">Principal\u2013agent problem</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Footnotes\">Footnotes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Cover_your_ass&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Footnotes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Miller, Korin (February 1, 2012). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.cosmopolitan.com/career/advice/a3784/what-to-do-after-getting-laid-off-013112/\">\"Do This Immediately After Getting Laid Off\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/Cosmopolitan_(magazine)\" title=\"Cosmopolitan (magazine)\">Cosmopolitan</a></i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">August 26,</span> 2014</span>. <q>If you're handed a pink slip, ... make these moves to cover your butt ....</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Cosmopolitan&amp;rft.atitle=Do+This+Immediately+After+Getting+Laid+Off&amp;rft.date=2012-02-01&amp;rft.aulast=Miller&amp;rft.aufirst=Korin&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cosmopolitan.com%2Fcareer%2Fadvice%2Fa3784%2Fwhat-to-do-after-getting-laid-off-013112%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACover+your+ass\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-twsSafire-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-twsSafire_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-twsSafire_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-twsSafire_2-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-twsSafire_2-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\"><a href=\"/wiki/William_Safire\" title=\"William Safire\">Safire, William</a> (August 18, 1987). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/1987/08/16/magazine/on-language-glossary-of-a-scandal.html\">\"On Language: Glossary of a Scandal\"</a>. <i>The New York Times</i>. pp.&#160;163\u2013164<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">August 26,</span> 2014</span>. <q>[A] new sense has evolved that uses the word for the posterior as a synecdoche for the whole person ... the initials today are an anachronism ...</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+New+York+Times&amp;rft.atitle=On+Language%3A+Glossary+of+a+Scandal&amp;rft.pages=163-164&amp;rft.date=1987-08-18&amp;rft.aulast=Safire&amp;rft.aufirst=William&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F1987%2F08%2F16%2Fmagazine%2Fon-language-glossary-of-a-scandal.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACover+your+ass\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Flanagan, Caitlin (November 1, 2007). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2007/11/no-girlfriend-of-mine/306329/2/\">\"No Girlfriend of Mine\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Atlantic\" title=\"The Atlantic\">The Atlantic</a></i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">August 26,</span> 2014</span>. <q>...cover-your-ass devotion to documentation and paperwork ....</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Atlantic&amp;rft.atitle=No+Girlfriend+of+Mine&amp;rft.date=2007-11-01&amp;rft.aulast=Flanagan&amp;rft.aufirst=Caitlin&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theatlantic.com%2Fmagazine%2Farchive%2F2007%2F11%2Fno-girlfriend-of-mine%2F306329%2F2%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACover+your+ass\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-twsAtlantic-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-twsAtlantic_4-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-twsAtlantic_4-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Ricks, Thomas E. (October 24, 2012). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2012/11/general-failure/309148/\">\"General Failure\"</a>. <i>The Atlantic</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">August 26,</span> 2014</span>. <q>... appropriate risk-taking diminished (the art of combat pursuit was almost lost in Vietnam), and a 'cover your ass' mentality took hold ....</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Atlantic&amp;rft.atitle=General+Failure&amp;rft.date=2012-10-24&amp;rft.aulast=Ricks&amp;rft.aufirst=Thomas+E.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theatlantic.com%2Fmagazine%2Farchive%2F2012%2F11%2Fgeneral-failure%2F309148%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACover+your+ass\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">McArdle, Megan (April 10, 2009). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2009/04/the-heroes-of-financial-fraud/12989/\">\"The Heroes of Financial Fraud\"</a>. <i>The Atlantic</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">August 26,</span> 2014</span>. <q>The instinct to CYA is a normal human emotion ....</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Atlantic&amp;rft.atitle=The+Heroes+of+Financial+Fraud&amp;rft.date=2009-04-10&amp;rft.aulast=McArdle&amp;rft.aufirst=Megan&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theatlantic.com%2Fbusiness%2Farchive%2F2009%2F04%2Fthe-heroes-of-financial-fraud%2F12989%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACover+your+ass\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Dixon, David, ed. (1999). \"A Culture of Corruption\". <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=MPihGaHK8jwC&amp;pg=PA110&amp;lpg=PA110&amp;dq=(%22cover+your+ass%22)+OR+%22cover+your+butt%22+OR+%22cover+your+rear+end%22)+corruption&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=c_E2qdi9tF&amp;sig=80SH7v54r3UuJ_cuThfGKlwsr40&amp;hl=en&amp;sa=X&amp;ei=hPD8U-XFPIOgyASdwYGoAg&amp;ved=0CCUQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&amp;q=(%22cover%20your%20ass%22)%20OR%20%22cover%20your%20butt%22%20OR%20%22cover%20your%20rear%20end%22)%20corruption&amp;f=false\"><i>A Culture of Corruption: Changing an Australian Police Service</i></a>. Hawkins Press<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">August 26,</span> 2014</span>  &#8211; via Google Books. <q>This 'cover your ass' perspective pervades all of patrol work ... bureaucratic paranoia ... not take the initiative on the street ....</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=A+Culture+of+Corruption&amp;rft.btitle=A+Culture+of+Corruption%3A+Changing+an+Australian+Police+Service&amp;rft.pub=Hawkins+Press&amp;rft.date=1999&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DMPihGaHK8jwC%26pg%3DPA110%26lpg%3DPA110%26dq%3D%28%2522cover%2Byour%2Bass%2522%29%2BOR%2B%2522cover%2Byour%2Bbutt%2522%2BOR%2B%252